<h2 id="basic-principles-of-decision-trees" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#basic-principles-of-decision-trees"><span>Basic Principles of Decision Trees</span></a></h2>
<p>A decision tree is a tree-like structure used for classification and regression models. It divides the data into different subsets through a series of questions, ultimately providing a prediction.</p>
<h3 id="structure-of-a-decision-tree" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#structure-of-a-decision-tree"><span>Structure of a Decision Tree</span></a></h3>
<p>A decision tree consists of the following parts:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Root Node</strong>: The starting node that contains all the samples.</li>
<li><strong>Internal Nodes</strong>: Represent feature test conditions.</li>
<li><strong>Branches</strong>: Represent the result of a test condition.</li>
<li><strong>Leaf Nodes</strong>: Represent the final classification or regression result.</li>
</ul>
