<h2 id="advantages-and-disadvantages-of-decision-trees" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#advantages-and-disadvantages-of-decision-trees"><span>Advantages and Disadvantages of Decision Trees</span></a></h2>
<h3 id="advantages" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#advantages"><span>Advantages</span></a></h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Easy to understand and interpret</strong>: Decision trees offer a clear, visual representation of the decision process.</li>
<li><strong>No need for feature scaling</strong>: They are not sensitive to the scale of features.</li>
<li><strong>Handle both numerical and categorical features</strong>: No need for special encoding.</li>
<li><strong>Handle multi-class problems</strong>: Naturally supports multi-class classification.</li>
<li><strong>Can handle missing values</strong>: Can learn patterns to handle missing data.</li>
</ol>
<h3 id="disadvantages" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#disadvantages"><span>Disadvantages</span></a></h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Prone to overfitting</strong>: Especially when the tree depth is large.</li>
<li><strong>Unstable</strong>: Small changes in data can result in significant changes in the tree structure.</li>
<li><strong>Bias towards features with many values</strong>: Tends to prefer features with more values.</li>
<li><strong>Difficult to learn certain relationships</strong>: Such as XOR relationships.</li>
<li><strong>Limited predictive performance</strong>: A single tree usually performs worse than ensemble methods.</li>
</ol>
<div class="knowledge-card">
  <div class="knowledge-card__title">
    <span class="icon">⚠️</span> Common Pitfalls
  </div>
  <div class="knowledge-card__content">
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Neglecting pruning</strong>: Failing to prune the tree properly can lead to overfitting.</li>
      <li><strong>Over-relying on a single tree</strong>: Not considering ensemble methods for complex problems.</li>
      <li><strong>Ignoring class imbalance</strong>: Not using the class_weight parameter to address imbalanced data.</li>
      <li><strong>Misinterpreting feature importance</strong>: Feature importance does not imply causality.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>
<h2 id="improvements-and-extensions-to-decision-trees" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#improvements-and-extensions-to-decision-trees"><span>Improvements and Extensions to Decision Trees</span></a></h2>
<p>To overcome the limitations of decision trees, various improvements and extensions have been developed:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Random Forest</strong>: Builds multiple trees and averages/votes the results.</li>
<li><strong>Gradient Boosting Trees</strong>: Builds trees sequentially using gradient boosting.</li>
<li><strong>XGBoost/LightGBM</strong>: Efficient implementations of gradient boosting trees.</li>
</ol>
